            <div class="strategy-title" onclick="toggleContent('strategy1')">Crop Rotation &#8595;</div>
            <div id="strategy1" class="strategy-content">
                <p>Crop rotation is a versatile and ecologically sound strategy that not only mitigates pests and diseases but also promotes overall farm health. 
                    Successful implementation requires careful planning, understanding of crop interactions, and consideration of local climate and soil conditions. 
                    By incorporating crop rotation into their practices, farmers can build resilient and sustainable agricultural systems for the benefit of both the land and future generations.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><b>Breaking Pest Cycles:</b>
                            One of the primary benefits of crop rotation is its ability to disrupt the life cycles of pests and pathogens. 
                            Many pests are host-specific, meaning they target particular crops. By changing the crop planted in a field, 
                            farmers can break the life cycle of pests that rely on a continuous supply of their preferred host.</li><br />
                        <li><b>Soil Health Improvement:</b>
                            Different crops have varying nutrient needs and interactions with the soil. 
                            Continuous cultivation of the same crop in a field can deplete specific nutrients while promoting the buildup of pathogens and pests associated with that crop. 
                            Crop rotation helps restore soil fertility by diversifying nutrient demands and enhancing beneficial microbial activity.</li><br />
                        <li><b>Disease Prevention:</b>
                            Many plant diseases persist in the soil and affect specific crop types. By rotating crops, farmers can prevent the buildup of soil-borne diseases. 
                            This is particularly important for diseases that survive on crop residues or in the soil for an extended period.</li>
                    </ol>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="strategy-container">
            <div class="strategy-title" onclick="toggleContent('strategy2')">Companion Planting &#8595;</div>
            <div id="strategy2" class="strategy-content">
                <p>Companion planting is an age-old agricultural technique where different plant species are grown together to enhance each other's growth, protect against pests, and improve overall crop yield. 
                    This method relies on the interactions between specific plants to create a more balanced and sustainable ecosystem. 
                    Here's a closer look at how companion planting can be effectively used for pest mitigation:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><b>Deterrent Plants:</b>
                        Companion planting is an age-old agricultural technique where different plant species are grown together to enhance each other's growth, protect against pests, and improve overall crop yield. 
                        This method relies on the interactions between specific plants to create a more balanced and sustainable ecosystem. 
                        Here's a closer look at how companion planting can be effectively used for pest mitigation:</li><br />
                    <li><b>Trap Crops</b>
                        Trap cropping involves planting specific plants to attract pests away from primary crops. 
                        These sacrificial plants serve as a trap for pests, reducing the damage to the main crops. 
                        For instance, planting nasturtiums to attract aphids or marigolds to attract nematodes can help protect nearby vegetables.</li><br />
                    <li><b>Polyculture Diversity: </b>
                        Growing a diverse range of plants in close proximity discourages the buildup of pests that specialize in attacking specific crops. 
                        The variety disrupts the pest's ability to locate and target their preferred host plants. 
                        This is an essential aspect of polyculture, where different crops are cultivated together.</li><br />
                </ol>
            </div>
