        <div class="strategy-container">
            <div class="strategy-title" onclick="toggleContent('strategy5')">Integrated Pest Management &#8595;</div>
            <div id="strategy5" class="strategy-content">
                <p>Integrated Pest Management (IPM) is a comprehensive and sustainable approach to managing pests that combines various strategies to minimize economic, environmental, and health risks. 
                    Unlike conventional pest control methods that heavily rely on chemical pesticides, IPM integrates biological, cultural, mechanical, and chemical control tactics. </p>
                <ol>
                    <li><b>Monitoring and Identification: </b><br />
                        Regular Surveillance: Implementing a monitoring system to regularly inspect crops for pest presence and assess population levels. <br />
                        Pest Identification: Identifying the specific pests involved allows for targeted and effective control measures.
                        </li><br />
                    <li><b>Mechanical and Physical Control: </b><br />
                        Barriers and Traps: Implementing physical barriers like row covers and traps to prevent pests from reaching crops or to capture them. <br />
                        Cultural Practices: Using techniques such as plowing and tilling to disrupt the habitat of pests and reduce their populations.</li><br />
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="strategy-container">
            <div class="strategy-title" onclick="toggleContent('strategy6')">Proper Crop Spacing &#8595;</div>
            <div id="strategy6" class="strategy-content">
                <p>Proper crop spacing is a fundamental component of pest mitigation strategies that align with sustainable and integrated approaches to agriculture. 
                    By recognizing the interconnectedness of plant spacing with disease prevention, pest deterrence, and ecosystem health, farmers can optimize their fields for resilience and productivity. 
                    Implementing these practices requires a holistic understanding of the specific needs of each crop, the local environment, and the overarching goal of promoting a balanced and thriving agricultural ecosystem.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><b>Optimising Nutrient Intake: </b>
                            Preventing Competition: Closely spaced crops may compete for nutrients, leading to weaker plants that are more susceptible to pest attacks. Well-spaced plants can access nutrients more efficiently and develop stronger immune systems.<br />
                            Avoiding Overcrowding: Overcrowded conditions can stress plants, making them more vulnerable to pests. Proper spacing provides each plant with adequate resources, promoting robust growth.</li><br />
                        <li><b>Preventing Disease Spread: </b>
                                Air Circulation: Proper spacing allows for better air circulation between plants, reducing humidity and minimizing conditions favorable for the spread of fungal diseases. Diseases like powdery mildew and certain blights thrive in damp, crowded environments.<br/>
                                Sunlight Exposure: Adequate spacing ensures that each plant receives sufficient sunlight. Sunlight is a natural disinfectant and can inhibit the development and spread of certain diseases.</li><br />
                        <li><b>Reducing Pest Infestations: </b>
                            Disruption of Pheromone Trails: Insects often communicate through pheromones, and closely spaced plants can create continuous paths for pests to follow. Proper spacing disrupts these trails, making it harder for pests to locate and infest new plants.<br />
                            Natural Predation: Spacing plants strategically allows natural predators, such as beneficial insects and birds, to navigate the area more effectively. This can lead to a more balanced ecosystem where pests are kept in check.</li><br />

                    </ol>
            </div>
        </div>

