        <div class="strategy-container">
            <div class="strategy-title" onclick="toggleContent('strategy12')">Weather Monitoring &#8595;</div>
            <div id="strategy12" class="strategy-content">
                <p>Weather monitoring is a fundamental component of integrated pest management, providing farmers with valuable insights into the dynamic interactions between weather patterns and pest behavior. 
                    By leveraging technology, historical data, and predictive models, farmers can enhance their ability to anticipate, prevent, and manage pest-related challenges, ultimately contributing to the resilience and sustainability of agricultural practices.</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><b>Predicting Pest Activity: </b>
                        Temperature and Activity Correlation: Warmer temperatures often correlate with increased pest activity. Monitoring temperature trends allows farmers to anticipate periods of heightened pest pressure and take preventive measures accordingly.<br />
                        Precipitation Impact: Rainfall patterns can influence the prevalence of certain pests, particularly those that thrive in humid conditions. Monitoring precipitation helps in assessing the risk of diseases and adjusting management strategies.</li><br />
                    <li><b>Predicting Pest Activity: </b>
                        Temperature and Activity Correlation: Warmer temperatures often correlate with increased pest activity. Monitoring temperature trends allows farmers to anticipate periods of heightened pest pressure and take preventive measures accordingly.<br />
                        Precipitation Impact: Rainfall patterns can influence the prevalence of certain pests, particularly those that thrive in humid conditions. Monitoring precipitation helps in assessing the risk of diseases and adjusting management strategies.</li><br />
                    <li><b>Wind Patterns and Pest Movement: </b>
                        Humidity and Fungal Diseases: High humidity levels contribute to the development and spread of fungal diseases. Weather monitoring helps in identifying conditions conducive to diseases like powdery mildew and downy mildew, enabling early detection and intervention.<br />
                        Leaf Wetness Monitoring: Sensors that measure leaf wetness provide real-time data on moisture levels, aiding in predicting the risk of diseases that thrive in wet conditions.</li><br />
                    <li><b>Wind Patterns and Pest Movement: </b>
                        Aerial Pests: Certain pests, especially insects, can be transported over long distances by wind currents. Monitoring wind patterns helps anticipate the arrival of migratory pests and implement control measures in advance.<br />
                        Spore Dispersal: Fungal and bacterial diseases often spread through airborne spores. Understanding wind patterns assists in predicting the movement of these spores, guiding decisions on fungicide applications.<br />
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>

